, returns home just in time for a planned reunion with the other four knights, one being Robin, he fought with in [[Acre, Israel]], but treachery awaits Robin in the castle of his old friend who has done a deal with the Sheriff to reclaim his castle forfeited while on the crusades. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=27\n|EpisodeNumber=103\n|Title=The Youthful Menace\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|3|9|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Arthur Dales\n|DirectedBy=Robert Day\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Marian's young cousin, the disinherited 16-year-old Edwin ([[Peter Kerr (actor)|Peter Kerr]]), arrives in Nottingham from France; he is scornful of the outlaws. He follows Marian to Robin's camp, and to keep his silence Robin must teach him to be a man by letting Edwin take him to the sheriff as his prisoner.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=28\n|EpisodeNumber=104\n|Title=The Doctor\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|3|16|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Leslie Poynton\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Little John suffers a bad fall breaking his leg and the local doctor is away so he is taken to the home of Sir George Woodley ([[John Harvey (actor)|John Harvey]]), where an Italian doctor, Benvolio ([[Henry Vidon]]), is visiting. Betrayed the doctor and Little John are arrested. Robin and Tuck's rescue attempt succeeds in rescuing the doctors but not Little John. The Sheriff is badly wounded by Robin Hood and a bargain is made by the doctor to save both Little John and the Sheriff. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=29\n|EpisodeNumber=105\n|Title=The Double\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|3|22|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Basil Dawson\n|DirectedBy=Gerry Bryant\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Prince John has ordered the Sheriff to Kill Prince Arthur, and Bolbec ([[John Gabriel (actor)|John Gabriel]]), has found a double, Luke Tanner, for Robin Hood and the sheriff hatches a plan for the double to kill the Prince. When Lady Constance ([[Pamela Alan]]), Prince Arthur ([[Richard O'Sullivan]]) and their Emissary ([[Richard Thorp]]) arrive in Sherwood and meet Robin Hood who knows of the plans from Friar Tuck and has to save the Prince and Luke Tanner. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=30\n|EpisodeNumber=106\n|Title=At the Sign of the Blue Boar\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|3|23|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Sidney B. Wells\n|DirectedBy=Ernest Bornemann\n|ShortSummary=OPENING SCENE CHORUS (Merry men singing at Blue Boar Inn): \"Thar 'hue and cry' rang out my lads! They trailed us to the glen, the glen! The Sheriff's breath was lost my lads, on Sherwood's merry men! From out the noose we slithered loose his lordship fooled again, again! Thar 'hue and cry' rang out my lads! They trailed us to the glen, the glen! The Sheriff's breath was lost my lads, on Sherwood's merry men! So sing and send a cheery note bring out your billed and then and then, the Sheriff will n'er be called mein host, by Sherwood's Merry Men!\"<br />SUMMARY: When a Tailor, Master William Blount ([[Geoffrey Chater]]) covets the ownership of the Blue Boar Inn, The Sheriff places a 'head tax' on the owner Ulrich ([[Martin Wyldeck]]), forcing him to sell the Inn to Blount, in exchange the Sheriff wants the Tailor to become an informer on Robin's outlaw gang, Robin disguised as Sir Guy puts matters straight. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=31\n|EpisodeNumber=107\n|Title= Quickness of the Hand\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|3|30|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=R.W.Bogany\n|DirectedBy=Robert Day\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The Sheriff issues a notice of a reward of 750 crowns for the capture of Robin Hood alive. Three bored knights Sir John ([[Brian Oulton]]), Sir Ralph ([[Richard Caldicot]]) and Sir Lawrence ([[Richard Pascoe]]) take up the offer and end up in Sherwood Forest disguised as magicians to pull off a vanishing act, the capture of Robin Hood. Friar Tuck spies the Sheriff's men lying in wait and saves the day. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=32\n|EpisodeNumber=108\n|Title= Elixir of Youth\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|4|6|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Samuel B. West\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Sir Boland ([[Patrick Troughton]]) intends to sell his niece, Lady Mellisa ([[Anne Reid]]) who is in love with the lords' squire Alwyn ([[Kenneth Cope]]), for 500 crowns to old Sir Louis de Panay ([[Reginald Beckwith]]). Maid Marian and Tuck determine to stop him. From Tuck, Robin deduces that Sir Louis wants to regain his lost youth, and Robin conjures a phoney story and 'Elixir of Youth' to sell for 500 crowns.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=33\n|EpisodeNumber=109\n|Title=The Genius\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|4|13|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Oliver Skene (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The Abbott ([[Charles Lloyd-Pack]]) calls on Friar Tuck to take Master Nicodemus ([[Harry H. Corbett]]), a fellow monk and master mathematician, to safety in Sherwood, Prince John has heard of his ideas on mathematics in warfare and wishes to take advantage of them, Count De Severne ([[Geoffrey Bayldon]]) has been sent to capture him and has taken his brother hostage, Robin puts the monks intelligence to work on a mighty weapon that wins the day. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=34\n|EpisodeNumber=110\n|Title=The Fire\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|4|20|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Philip Bolsover\n|DirectedBy=Robert Day\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: During a heatwave the Sheriff's men corner Derwent & Little John in a cave, the Lieutenant's (Paul Eddington) attempt to smoke them out leads to a forest fire, forcing Robin and the Sheriff to work together in a truce to save Sherwood and Nottingham but the Sheriff's word is tested when Robin is trapped under a fallen branch.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=35\n|EpisodeNumber=111\n|Title=The Minstrel\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|4|27|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Leslie Poynton\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=OPENING SCENE: Minstrel Roland \u2013 Song 1:\"What is a body without a head and what is supper without good bread; the land needs more than a minstrel's poem. My King, my King, my King hurry home!\". He then enquires about the Sheriff and improvises on request \u2013 Song 2:\"Picture a pig all in braid and lace, a billy goat beard on a weasel's face; a snake for a sire (a male parent of a horse), a dog for a dam (a female horse), and that is the Sheriff of Nottingham!\" Informed that the Sheriff robs he composes \u2013 Song 3:\"Here is a man that can pick a purse, he robs the cradle he robs the hearse; his eye at your window, his thumb in your [[jamb]], that's the greedy old Sheriff of Nottingham!\"<br />SUMMARY: Marian brings Roland the Minstrel ([[Francis Matthews (actor)|Francis Matthews]]), exiled from London for derogatory songs about Prince John, to Sherwood, Prince John ([[Brian Haines]]) and the Ambassador of [[Aragon]] ([[Roger Delgado]]) are to visit Nottingham to sign a treaty, so the Sheriff locks up all strangers including the minstrel in order to avert any show of disrespect for authority in the area, Robin decides to use Roland's song about the Sheriff (see song 2 & 3 above) to his advantage, soon all Nottingham is singing it (and adding new verses as it spreads). Robin rescues Roland and Friar Tuck organises the children (includes [[Jane Asher]]) to sing for the Ambassador.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=36\n|EpisodeNumber=112\n|Title=The Lottery\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|5|4|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Peter Yeldham\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Two Rafflers, Will Sharpe ([[Alfred Burke]]) and his accomplice Frisby (Ian Whittaker) arrive in Nottingham, with a fixed lottery game, when the Sheriff takes over the game, Robin, Marian and Tuck devise a plan to declare the Sheriff's lottery null and void and return the money to the people. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=37\n|EpisodeNumber=113\n|Title=Lincoln Green\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|5|11|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Neil R. Collins\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The ex-employee of David ([[Geoffrey Chater]]), Master Draper of Lincoln Town, named Simon Shanks ([[Charles Houston (actor)|Charles Houston]]) tries to sell inferior Lincoln green cloth to the band but his wares are rejected, and he goes to the Sheriff. Robin, Marian & Little John go to Lincoln and Robin and Little John are captured by the Sheriff and imprisoned in the tower of Lincoln Castle.  Marian devises a plan using a bolt of cloth, a sling, and a spindle made by David to rescue Robin and John. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=38\n|EpisodeNumber=114\n|Title=Women's War\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|5|18|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Philip Bolsover\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Anne De Brissac ([[Zena Walker]]) asks the outlaws to help her with a box full of gold she claims is intended for King Richard, Marian informs Robin that the Lady is on the side of Prince John. Little John and Ned who have gone to collect the gold go missing, and it is up to Marian to force the truth from Anne, before the Sheriff closes the trap. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=39\n|EpisodeNumber=115\n|Title=Little Mother\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|5|25|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Philip Bolsover\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The Duke of Retford ([[Charles Houston (actor)|Charles Houston]]) sets a trap for Little John, when he goes to see his injured mother ([[Ren\u00e9e Houston]]). Despite Friar Tuck and Maid Marian's warning Little John is captured and Robin and the band rush to his aid.\nNOTE: Desmond Llewelyn, \"Q\" in the James Bond films, appears as \"Two Fingers.\"|LineColor=195905  \n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=40\n|EpisodeNumber=116\n|Title=Marian's Prize\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|6|1|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Louis Marks\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Marian enters an archery contest in place of Robin, Prince John ([[Donald Pleasence]]) visiting Northeave village, ups the prize money to 20 crowns, hoping to draw in Robin Hood. Marian disguised as \"Martin\" wins the contest but Robin disguised as \"Hugh\" is tempted and challenges Martin not realising Prince John is waiting.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=41\n|EpisodeNumber=117\n|Title=Farewell to Tuck\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|6|22|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Arthur Dales\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The Sheriff tries to convince The Archbishop (Carl Bernard) to move Friar Tuck to another parish, but he doesn't bargain for the Archbishop's knowledge of Robin Hood, or his faith in Friar Tuck.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series 4 (1958\u201359)===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"\n|- style=\"color:#FFFFFF\"\n!style=\"background:#AC1F1F; width:30px\"|N\u00ba\n!style=\"background:#AC1F1F; width:20px\"|Ep\n!style=\"background:#AC1F1F\"|Title\n!style=\"background:#AC1F1F\"|Director\n!style=\"background:#AC1F1F\"|Screenplay\n!style=\"background:#AC1F1F; width:135px\"|Original air date\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=1\n|EpisodeNumber=118\n|Title=Sybella\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|9|14|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Michael Connor\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Baron Oslow ([[David Davies (actor born 1906)|David Davies]]) murders the Earl of Steyne and steals his identity, The Juggler Ali ([[Michael Peake]]) over hears him plotting with the Sheriff to sail to the Holy Land and kill King Richard and is also killed. Ali's partner Sybella ([[Soraya Rafat]]) who has an amazing memory can hardly speak English, tries to warn Robin but it is Maid Marian who falls foul of the false Earl of Steyne.<br 