kes precedence, for a fee, while Robin and Will Scarlet breach a dam.<br />NOTE: this episode, apart from three or so studio scenes, is shot almost entirely on location.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=5\n|EpisodeNumber=122\n|Title=The Flying Sorcerer\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|10|12|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Palmer Thompson\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Lord Giles ([[Anthony Jacobs (actor)|Anthony Jacobs]]) arrives in Nottingham to uncover tax evasions, to avoid more tax problems the Sheriff puts forward a plan to have the eccentric Lord Almar ([[Arthur Howard]]) accused of being a sorcerer, and his lands given over to Lord Giles. Marian tries to help but Almar is arrested and Robin comes to his aid, and the eccentric Lord's interest in flight comes to Robin's aid as a kite. \n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=6\n|EpisodeNumber=123\n|Title=The Loaf\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|10|19|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Philip Bolsover\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: A boy steals a loaf of bread from the Sheriff's men, Friar Tuck gives him sanctuary in the local church, but after 40 days, under the law of sanctuary, the boy will have to leave the country. The Sheriff demands 500 loaves to free the boy by the next midday and Robin devises a plan to obtain the Sheriff's supply of flour to fulfil the demand.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=7\n|EpisodeNumber=124\n|Title=Six Strings to his Bow\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|10|26|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Raymond Bowers\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=OPENING SCENE: Song by minstrel Sir Alan-a-Dale with harp: \"The sign of the Blue Boar, hangs beyond the door; the serving girl called Joan, has left me to drink alone!\"<br />SUMMARY: Intro Sir Alan-a-Dale ([[Richard Coleman]]). Unaware that Prince John has accused him of murder and declared an outlaw. In warning Sir Alan, Marian is wounded by a crossbow bolt threatening to reveal her identity to the pursuing Sheriff.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=8\n|EpisodeNumber=125\n|Title=The Devil You Don't Know\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|11|2|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Owen Holder\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The Sheriff of Nottingham is preparing to leave for 3 months duty in London, Sir Alan-a-Dale ([[Richard Coleman]]) is missing from Robin's camp and presumed held captive by the Sheriff. Robin and Will Scarlet intercept the Deputy Sheriff and free a prisoner, the mysterious Ralph of Plumtree, and he insists on impersonating the Deputy Sheriff to discover if Sir Alan is a prisoner. The Deputy Sheriff lays a trap for both Robin and Marian.<br />NOTE: Last appearance of the Sheriff of Nottingham ([[Alan Wheatley]]) and intro of the Deputy Sheriff ([[John Arnatt]]).\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=9\n|EpisodeNumber=126\n|Title=Goodbye Little John\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|11|9|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Raymond Bowers\n|DirectedBy=Robert Day\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Little John returns to Sherwood Forest and finds his place in Robin's band taken by Will Scarlet and The Deputy Sheriff offers Little John a pardon.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=10\n|EpisodeNumber=127\n|Title=Hostage for a Hangman\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|11|16|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Arthur Dales\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The Deputy Sheriff tells Robin, during a truce, that he will hang two serfs everyday until Robin gives himself up. Robin calls on Marian's guests, two Lords who outrank the Deputy Sheriff, Alford ([[Humphrey Lestocq]]) and Beaumont ([[Jack Melford]]) to make the Deputy Sheriff show his true colours by dressing them as serfs and hanging them first. \n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=11\n|EpisodeNumber=128\n|Title=Hue and Cry\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|11|23|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Alan Hackney\n|DirectedBy=Compton Bennett\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The Deputy Sheriff's is attacked and his chain of office stolen in Lower Fitzwalter, a village of freemen. At the blacksmith of William ([[Kevin Stoney]]) [[Hue and cry]] is invoked under the rule of [[Frankpledge]] and if the attacker cannot be found nine men will hang. Robin, Marian, her maid Jenny ([[Geraldine Hagan]]) who had teased Dick ([[Ronald Hines]]) the [[Swineherd]], the thief, provide the solution.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=12\n|EpisodeNumber=129\n|Title=The Reluctant Rebel\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|11|30|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Leon Griffiths\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Sir Geoffrey (John Carson) and his serf Herbert (Leslie Phillips) pose as outlaw Jim Stark and his lieutenant to join Robin's gang, for information on the outlaw life for Sir Geoffrey's journals. \n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=13\n|EpisodeNumber=130\n|Title=The Oath\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|12|7|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Arthur Dales\n|DirectedBy=Compton Bennett\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The Deputy Sheriff tries to turn the Archbishop ([[Carl Bernard]]) against Friar Tuck implicating him with the outlaws. Tuck takes an oath in front of the Archbishop not to reveal the identity or the location of the Sheriff's latest prisoner, an envoy of King Richard, about to be hung and Tuck cannot break his oath and tell Robin to save the man, so he calls a special service at the church.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=14\n|EpisodeNumber=131\n|Title=The Debt\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|12|14|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Leon Griffiths\n|DirectedBy=Anthony Squire\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: A former Crusader friend of Robin's, Martin ([[Brian Rawlinson]]), who saved his life seven years before at the crusade, masquerades as one of Robin's gang and begins robbing travellers entering Sherwood forest, including Friar Tuck, and fatally wounding John Dale (Terry Yorke) in his home.  Martin wants to join Robin's band and when he learns Friar Tuck and Marian know Robin he has the upper hand. Robin has to make him leave bearing in mind the debt he owes this man.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=15\n|EpisodeNumber=132\n|Title=The Charm Pedlar\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|12|14|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Alan Hackney\n|DirectedBy=Peter Seabourne\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: A Charm Pedlar named Hugo ([[Victor Maddern]]) arrives in Nottingham, Lady Marian takes against him for getting the locals to waste their money on his phoney potions, she gets the Deputy Sheriff involved to arrest Hugo. Robin, at the behest of Friar Tuck, disguises himself as a fellow con-man to investigate the pedlar's activities and finds himself rounded up with the Charm Pedlar in the Sheriff's dungeon, both to be hanged to Marian's horror.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=16\n|EpisodeNumber=133\n|Title=The Bagpiper\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|12|21|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Jan Read\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Duncan of Stoneykirk ([[Hugh McDermott (actor)|Hugh McDermott]]) makes a return visit to Sherwood forest, still with an eye for Marian, only this time he has a plan to win a bagpiping contest against Tam McKinnon ([[Andrew Downie]]) at the castle of Sir Fulke ([[Patrick Troughton]]), or so he claims, Robin dressed in highland garb and beard accompanies him and Duncan's intention is revealed although Duncan is wounded in the process.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=17\n|EpisodeNumber=134\n|Title=The Parting Guest\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|12|28|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Louis Marks\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Still hanging around Robin's camp Duncan turns his attentions to the Lady Marian until his lassie Jessie ([[Ellen McIntosh]]) arrives to take Duncan back home. Refusing to leave Robin, after Will Scarlet refuses, tries to woo Jessie to make him jealous but it is Marian who is jealous. Robin arranges an archery contest between Marian and Jessie for five gold crowns to set Duncan on the road to Scotland. \n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=18\n|EpisodeNumber=135\n|Title=A Race Against Time\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1959|1|4|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Arthur Dales\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Will Scarlet witness the murder of an envoy and he and Robin capture Wilfred ([[Michael Ripper]]) who had led the envoy into the trap. They discover that the killer was Sir Hartley ([[David Davies (actor born 1906)|David Davies]]) who intends to kill [[Constance, Duchess of Brittany]] ([[Patricia Marmont]]) and [[Arthur I, Duke of Brittany|Prince Arthur]] (Jonathan Bailey) as they pass through Sherwood to Northumberland.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=19\n|EpisodeNumber=136\n|Title=The Pharaoh Stones\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1959|1|11|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=William Templeton\n|DirectedBy=Gordon Parry\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Little John acquires 'The Pharaoh Stones', stones that predict the future, from a pedlar (Carl Bernard), and falls under their superstitious influence and the band is also convinced. Robin to regain his authority devises a plan with Will and Marian to break their spell but it leads to Little John's capture.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=20\n|EpisodeNumber=137\n|Title=Bride For An Outlaw\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1959|1|18|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Louis Marks\n|DirectedBy=Gordon Parry\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: To avoid capture in Nottingham by the Sheriff Robin is forced into a proxy marriage, performed by Friar Tuck, to Judith Denton (Mary Mason), the daughter of wealthy merchant Master Bligh Denton ([[John Horsley (actor)|John Horsley]]) who mistakes Robin for her real suitor Sir Peter Marston ([[Nigel Davenport]]). \n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=21\n|EpisodeNumber=138\n|Title=Double Trouble\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1959|1|25|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Louis Marks\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Friar Tuck's twin brother Edgar returns to Nottingham. The Deputy Sheriff imprisons Tuck and forces his brother Edgar to impersonate him, for the purpose of confessing his brothers 'sins', of aiding Robin and denouncing Maid Marian, to the Bishop ([[Charles Lloyd-Pack]]), Robin has to match the Deputy Sheriff's duplicity by capturing the Bishop and the Sheriff.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=22\n|EpisodeNumber=139\n|Title=Trapped\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1959|2|1|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Wilton Schiller\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Robin becomes the latest victim of Sir Hugo DeBask (Laurence Hardy), a lord who arrests travellers through his estate and sets them to work on his lands if they can't pay the fine he imposes at their trial, looking for him Marian also falls into the trap, escape comes from an unexpected quarter.<br />NOTE: Laurence Hardy's character is incorrectly billed as Sir Marmot on the end titles.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=23\n|EpisodeNumber=140\n|Title=The Champion\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1959|2|8|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Leon Griffiths\n|DirectedBy=Gordon Parry\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Marian has been informed by the Deputy Sheriff that her father has died in the Holy Land and Prince John has nominated Sir Guy Quentin ([[John Horsley (actor)|John Horsley]]) to take over her estate. Friar Tuck informs Marian her father is alive and she can appeal to the courts. Marian's sixty-year-old uncle Sir Percy ([[Jack Allen (actor)|Jack Allen]]) pre-empts this by challenging the much younger Quentin to a duel and Robin has to convince Quentin that Sir Percy is a fearsome fighter.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=24\n|EpisodeNumber=141\n|Title=The Edge and the Point\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1959|2|15|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Raymond Bowers\n|DirectedBy=Gordon Parry\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Boland ([[Michael Gough]]) a former Crusader defeats Will Scarlet and then Robin Hood in a swordfight and is only prevented from killing him by Maid Marian's prowess with the bow. Boland offers his services to the Deputy Sheriff and he makes him his lieutenant and takes sword-fighting lessons so he can kill Robin Hood himself and take the glory and become Sheriff. Robin Hood accepts the challenge in the hope of revealing the Deputy Sheriff's colours.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=25\n|EpisodeNumber=142\n|Title=A Bushel of Apples\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1959|2|22|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Jan Read\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: While Lord Ambrose is away at the Crusade, Sir Watkyn of Parstock ([[Harry H. Corbett]]) his bailiff, has been extorting heavy taxes from the tenants and serfs on his estate with menaces. Friar Tuck seeks Robin's help but is arrested as an outlaw and Robin contacts Father Ignatius ([[Philip Latham]]) Lord Ambrose priest, and with his aid puts paid to Watkyns' underhand schemes.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=26\n|EpisodeNumber=143\n|Title=The Truce\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1959|3|1|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Leon Griffiths\n|DirectedBy=Gordon Parry\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Needing to win an archery tournament against Lord Repton ([[Richard Caldicot]]), the Deputy Sheriff parleys a truce with Robin to be his archer for the day. His opponent is Mark Crispin ([[Derek Tansley]]), Champion Bowman of England.\n|LineColor=AC1F1F\n}}\n|}\n\nNote: CBS, having moved the game show ''[[Name That Tune]]'' from Tuesday nights to Monday nights at 7.30pm for the 1958 fall season, screened the fourth series in the US on Saturday mornings at 11.30am, after a batch of re-runs which started on 4 October 1958, the final episodes were transmitted between 10 January 1959 and 26 September 1959.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{tv.com episodes|the-adventures-of-robin-hood|10341|The Adventures of Robin Hood}}\n* {{IMDb episodes|0047706|The Adventures of Robin Hood}}\n* List of {{epguides|AdventuresofRobinHood|The Adventures of Robin Hood'' episodes}}\n* [http://www.boldoutlaw.com/robspot/greenerobin.html ''The Adventures of Robin Hood'': A Robin Hood Spotlight]\n* [https://archive.org/search.php?query=subject%3A%22The%20Adventures%20Of%20Robin%20Hood%22 Download episodes of ''The Adventures of Robin Hood''] at the [[Internet Archive]]\n\n{{Robin Hood}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adventures Of Robin Hood, The}}\n[[Category:Lists of British children's television series episodes|Adventures of Robin Hood]]\n[[Category:Lists of British period drama television series episodes|Adventures of Robin Hood]]\n[[Category:Lists of British action television series episodes|Adventures of Robin Hood]]\n\n[[nl:The Adventures of Robin Hood (serie)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''The Adventures of Robin Hood'' episodes}}\nThis is a list of episodes for the 1950s television series ''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood (TV series)|The Adventures of Robin Hood]]'', rarely shown as ''The Adventures in Sherwood Forest''; this show ran for 143 episodes across four series.\n\n==Home media==\n\n===VHS releases===\nITC Home Video (UK) released three double tape editions of the series.\n*\"The Beginning\" (14 October 1991) containing \"The Coming of Robin Hood\", \"The Moneylender\", \"Dead or Alive\", \"Friar Tuck\", \"Maid Marian\", \"A Guest For The Gallows\". 152 mins.\n*\"The Challenge\" (10 February 1992) containing \"The Knight Who Came to Dinner\", \"Queen Eleanor\", \"Checkmate\", \"The Ordeal\", \"The Inquisitor\", \"The Challenge\". 152 mins (ITC 8101).\n*\"The Thieves Den\" (22 June 1992) containing \"Pepper\", \"A Tuck in Time\", \"The Charter\", \"The Salt King\". 100 mins (ITC 8102)\nNetwork Video (UK) released videotape PAL versions beginning in 2003.\n\nMarathon Music and Video (US) released 21 VHS tapes of the series in 2000 (two episodes per tape in a random order).\n\n===DVD releases===\n''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood (TV series)|The Adventures of Robin Hood]]'' has been released by several companies, as under British law, TV episodes are only eligible for a total of 50 years of copyright.<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1995/3297/regulation/7/made The Duration of Copyright and Rights in Performances Regulations 1995] Retrieved 21-Mar-2011</ref>\n\nIn Universal Region ALL [[NTSC]] format, [[Mill Creek Entertainment]] have released all four seasons on DVD between 18 March 2008 and 25 August 2009, and eventually released a complete series set on 25 August 2009 \u2013 143 episodes on 11 discs. The films have been sourced from poor quality American prints, though some are from better quality European sources, some episodes feature the \"Adventures in Sherwood Forest\" opening titles and a few are CBS syndicated prints.  In addition, three episodes: \"Farewell To Tuck\", \"The Charm Pedlar\", \"The Parting Guest\" have no on-screen titles at all.<ref>[http://www.millcreekent.com/ViewProductDetails.asp?productid=502 Adventures of Robin Hood \u2013 The Complete Series]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, product information page at Mill Creek Entertainment website.</ref>\n\nIn Region 0 in NTSC format [[Alpha Video]] in the US have released twenty-two DVDs of various episodes from the series, each disc containing four episodes (88 episodes in total).<ref>[http://www.oldies.com/product-view/6439D.html Adventures of Robin Hood, Volume 22], Alpha Video product information page at Oldies.com.</ref>\n\nIn Region 0, series 1 & 4 and in Region 2, series 2 & 3 in [[PAL]] format, [[Network DVD]] has released the complete series in the UK in four boxed sets, licensed from official copyright holder [[Granada plc|Granada]] Ventures. The first three series have 39 episodes each and are on five-disc sets, while the last series has 26 episodes and is on three discs, the films have been taken from original Archive prints and are of variable quality. Three episodes feature French opening and end title sequences and no on-screen titles: \"Farewell To Tuck\", \"The Charm Pedlar\", \"The Parting Guest\". One episode, \"The Minstrel\", has French opening titles but original English end titles and retains the episode title.\n\nIn NTSC format, the first series has been released by Edi video (2005), TMG (Timeless Media Group) as a three DVD boxed set (2005) and by Pop Flix as a 4-disc collection (2010).  Other US companies such as Genius Entertainment, Critics Choice, Nostalgia Ventures, East West Entertainment, Digiview Productions, PC Treasures Inc, Echo Bridge Entertainment, and PR studios have released limited runs on DVD.\n\nIn Region 2 in PAL format, KNM Home Entertainment has released, in Germany, three DVD sets containing the 26 episodes (a mix of series 1 and 2 episodes) that were dubbed into German and transmitted by ARD between 1971 and 1974.\n\nA complete series 18-disc box set was released by Network DVD in December 2011 in Region 2.\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=2 rowspan=2|Series\n! rowspan=2|No. of<br /> episodes\n! colspan=2|Originally aired:\n! colspan=3|DVD releases\n|-\n! Premiered\n! Ended\n! colspan=1|{{nowrap|[[DVD region code|Universal Region 0]] / [[PAL]]}}\n! colspan=2|[[DVD region code|Universal Region ALL]] / [[NTSC]]\n|-\n| style=\"width:5px; background:#BFF0FF\"|\n! [[#Series 1 (1955\u201356)|1]]\n| 39\n| 25 September [[1955 in television|1955]]\n| 23 June [[1956 in television|1956]]\n| 30 June 2003<ref name=Am2/><br />3 March 2008<ref name=Am2>amazon.uk.co. Network set of DVDs issued in UK.</ref><br />[Network DVD (UK)]\n| rowspan=4| ''Complete Series''<br /> {{nowrap|25 August 2009}}<ref name=Am1>\namazon.com. Mill Creek Entertainment set of DVDs issued in U.S.</ref><br /> [Mill Creek Entertainment (US)]\n| 18 March 2008<ref name=Am1/> <br />[Mill Creek (US)]\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"F3CE4E\"|\n! [[#Series 2 (1956\u201357)|2]]\n| 39\n| 10 August 1956\n| 9 June [[1957 in television|1957]]\n| 30 June 2003<ref name=Am2/><br />26 April 2004<ref name=Am2/><br />1 December 2008<ref name=Am2/><br />[Network DVD (UK)]\n| 14 October 2008<ref name=Am1/><br />[Mill Creek (US)]\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"195905\"|\n! [[#Series 3 (1957\u201358)|3]]\n| 39\n| 6 September 1957\n| 22 June [[1958 in television|1958]]\n|align=\"center\" width=\"150px\"| 18 October 2004<ref name=Am2/><br />1 November 2008<ref name=Am2/><br />[Network DVD (UK)]\n|align=\"center\" width=\"150px\"| 31 March 2009<ref name=Am1/><br />[Mill Creek (US)]\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"AC1F1F\"|\n! [[#Series 4 (1958\u201359)|4]]\n| 26\n| 14 September 1958\n| 1 March [[1959 in television|1959]]\n| 24 January 2005<ref name=Am2/><br />[Network DVD (UK)]\n| 25 August 2009<ref name=Am1/><br />[Mill Creek (US)]\n|}\n\n==Episode list==\n* '''N\u00ba''' = Overall episode number\n* '''Ep''' = Episode number by series\n\nThis episode list shows the order and dates in which episodes were shown in the London region.  Episodes were first shown on different dates and sometimes out of sequence in other regions, the US and in other countries.\n\nAirdates are for ATV London <ref>Before 1968 ATV transmitted weekdays in the Midlands and weekends in London. See [[History of ITV]]</ref> [[ITV Network|ITV]] regions varied date and order. The order is taken from the British Film Institute database.<ref>http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/series/2761</ref>  (Except: \"Errand of Mercy\" (series 1) no BFI data, original US TX date used. \"The Goldmaker\" and \"Isabella\" (series 2) no BFI TX date for (1956/57) only (1961), original US TX dates used. \"The Salt King\" (series 3) 1st repeat BFI date used, as BFI 1st TX date places episode at start of series 2.)  IMDB gives broadcast dates and order shown in the US.\n\n===Notes to writers===\nMany writers on the show were Americans who had been blacklisted.  These writers worked under pseudonyms, often changing them after several episodes to avoid drawing attention to themselves.\n\nAs well, pseudonyms were sometimes shared between writers, or traded from one writer to another.  In particular, the names \"John Dyson\" and \"Neil R. Collins\" appear to have been assigned to various writers with no special affiliation to any one writer or writing team.\n\n*[[Ring Lardner, Jr.]] wrote the first episode under the name Lawrence McClellan.  This was later changed to the name Eric Heath for UK broadcast.\n*Ring Lardner, Jr. and [[Ian McLellan Hunter]] used a variety of pseudonyms when working individually or collaboratively.  Lardner's notes credit the following pseudonyms to work done by Lardner and/or Hunter:  Eric Heath, Oliver Skene, Samuel B. West, Ian Larkin, John Dyson, Leighton Reynolds, Paul Symonds, Neil R. Collins.\n*[[Waldo Salt]] wrote episodes under the name Arthur Behr, John Dyson and Neil R. Collins.<ref>http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/individual/89185 retrieved 6 March 2011</ref>\n*[[Howard Koch (screenwriter)|Howard Koch]] wrote episodes with his wife Anne as Anne Rodney.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bard.edu/archives/voices.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-08 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528012455/http://www.bard.edu/archives/voices.htm |archivedate=28 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }} Retrieved 7 March 2011</ref>\n*[[Adrian Scott]] wrote one episode as Leslie Poynton.  The name Leslie Poynton was used on several episodes; it is unknown which other writers may have used this pseudonym.\n*[[Robert Lees]] wrote several episodes, according to Lardner's papers, as John Dyson.  It has been suggested that C. Douglas Phipps (credited writer of episode 30) is another Lees pseudonym, although this is not confirmed.\n\n===Series 1 (1955\u201356)===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"\n!style=\"background:#BFF0FF; width:20px\"|N\u00ba\n!style=\"background:#BFF0FF; width:20px\"|Ep \n!style=\"background:#BFF0FF\"|Title\n!style=\"background:#BFF0FF\"|Director\n!style=\"background:#BFF0FF\"|Screenplay\n!style=\"background:#BFF0FF; width:135px\"|Original air date\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=1\n|EpisodeNumber2=1\n|Title=The Coming of Robin Hood\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|9|25|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Lawrence McClellan (on US prints) <br> Eric Heath (on UK prints) <br>(pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=[[Ralph Smart]]\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Robin of Locksley, a knight bold and good; back from the Holy Wars, becomes Robin Hood!\" <br />SUMMARY: Sir Robin of Locksley returns to England from fighting in the Crusades to discover that the notorious Sir Roger de Lille ([[Leo McKern]]) has been given his family's lands and castles, and has had Robin declared an outlaw. Robin takes refuge in Sherwood Forest and joins a band of outlaws led by Will Scatlock ([[Bruce Seton]]) who names him Robin of the hood. Features [[Alfie Bass]] as Edgar.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=2\n|EpisodeNumber2=2\n|Title=The Moneylender\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|10|2|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Ian Larkin and Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Trapped by the Sheriff, stands Robin like a mighty rock; and falls heir to the brave Will Scatlock!\"<br />SUMMARY: Robin and Edgar ([[Alfie Bass]]) lighten the load of a greedy, crooked moneylender Herbert of Doncaster (Leo McKern) by taking his purse full of money, and giving the contents of it back to the poor villagers and farmers from whom he took it. When Will Scatlock is mortally wounded, with his dying breath he passes the leadership of his gang over to Robin Hood.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=3\n|EpisodeNumber2=3\n|Title=Dead or Alive\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|10|9|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Eric Heath (screenwriter)|Eric Heath]] (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=[[Daniel Birt|Dan Birt]]\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Freedom is calling to Little John, the giant; Robin helps him understand, a serf can be defiant!\"<br />SUMMARY: The giant Little John escapes from his feudal lord and after being captured by the sheriff's men agrees to capture Robin Hood in exchange for his freedom.<br />NOTE: As well as being the first appearance of Archie Duncan as Little John this episode also features the first appearances of Simone Levell as Joan the Blue Boar barmaid and [[Bernadette O'Farrell]] as Maid Marian. \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=4\n|EpisodeNumber2=4\n|Title= Friar Tuck\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|10|16|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Mildred flees Sir William's trope, 'tis Harold she would rather wed; she seeks the aid of Friar Tuck, and vows are safely said!\"<br />SUMMARY: Robin Hood seeks out Friar Tuck to become the gang's spiritual aid, but becomes embroiled in Tuck's plans to help a young woman marry the man of her choosing, instead of Sir William of [[Malmesbury]] ([[Leslie Phillips]]), whom she has been pledged to marry by Lord Germaine ([[Douglas Wilmer]]), she being his [[serf]].\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=5\n|EpisodeNumber2=5\n|Title= Maid Marian\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|10|23|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Anne Rodney (pseudonym of [[Howard E. Koch|Howard Koch]] and Anne Koch)\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Robin Hood bold and free, of every man is unafraid; 'til one day he meets his match, with Marian the maid!\"<br />SUMMARY: Lady Marian Fitzwalter infiltrates the Merry Men, disguised as a page, to capture her childhood friend turned outlaw, Robin of Locksley.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=6\n|EpisodeNumber2=6\n|Title=The Inquisitor \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|11|6|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Anne Rodney (pseudonym of [[Howard E. Koch|Howard Koch]] and Anne Koch)\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"The Archbishop comes from France, King Richard's interests to pursue; Robin takes a daring chance, to tell him what is true!\"<br /> SUMMARY: When Friar Tuck is arrested and taken to be judged by The Archbishop ([[Jack Melford]]), Robin and Little John race to his aid.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=7\n|EpisodeNumber2=7\n|Title=The Knight Who Came To Dinner\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|11|13|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Eric Heath (screenwriter)|Eric Heath]] (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"In days of old when Knights were bold, and practiced arts of chivalry; there lived no sadder sight I'm told, than Sir Richard of the Lea!\" <br />SUMMARY: Intro Sir Richard of The Lea ([[Ian Hunter (actor)|Ian Hunter]]). Robin and the gang lend Sir Richard of the Lea the money he needs to pay off a debt owed to the corrupt Abbott Franklyn ([[Frank Royd]]) who is in league with the Sheriff of Nottingham.<br />NOTE: an alternative version of this episode also exists in the US (available streaming on Amazon Prime), where Sir Richard's debt is owed to the corrupt Baron Emmet, played by John Longden, in place of the Abbot.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=8\n|EpisodeNumber2=8\n|Title=The Challenge \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|11|20|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Giles Black and Robin Hood, archers of undoubted skill; loose their shafts on target range, but one is champion still!\"<br />SUMMARY: The Sheriff wagers with Sir Richard of the Lea that his archer, Giles Black, can defeat Robin Hood in an archery contest. \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=9\n|EpisodeNumber2=9\n|Title=Queen Eleanor \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|11|27|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Dan Birt\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Eleanor of Acquitane, to Nottingham for treasure goes; there to learn who are her friends, and those who are her foes!\"<br />SUMMARY: When [[Eleanor of Aquitaine|Queen Eleanor]] ([[Jill Esmond]]) arrives in Nottingham, her last port of call on her mission to collect funds for King Richard's war in the Holy Land, Lady Marian calls on Robin to give The Queen safe passage through Sherwood Forest.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=10\n|EpisodeNumber2=10\n|Title=Checkmate \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|12|4|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Peter Lambda\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Marian with ardent bloods, keeps Count de Walden occupied; through the castle all the while, his henchmen are defied!\" <br />SUMMARY: When Lady Marian is told by her Nanny ([[Marie Burke]]) that her grandson has been taken by Count de Walden's ([[Leslie Phillips]]) soldiers, Robin is soon at hand to uncover the Counts plans.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=11\n|EpisodeNumber2=11\n|Title=The Ordeal \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|12|11|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Dan Birt\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Murder in a village, an outlaw is the one accused; Robin sees that right and truth, shall triumph unabused!\"<br />SUMMARY: When Edgar ([[Alfie Bass]]) secretly visits his wife and child, he is spotted by a neighbour who reports him to the Sheriff of Nottingham and a plan is hatched to frame him for murder. \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=12\n|EpisodeNumber2=12\n|Title=A Guest for the Gallows\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|12|25|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Old Will Stuteley cannot pay, and into prison he is cast; the Sheriff is the very one, who turns him loose at last!\"<br />SUMMARY: Nottingham's tax collectors find it increasingly difficult to collect the county's levied assessments. When the Sheriff makes an example of poor farmer Will Stuteley, sentencing him to hang for non-payment of taxes, Robin Hood determines to rescue him. Tricking the Sheriff into Sherwood Forest alone, he is held captive and offered his life in exchange for the condemned man. \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=13\n|EpisodeNumber2=13\n|Title=The Highlander \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1955|12|25|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Strange tales are told of Robin Hood, but strangest far of all the lot; is when he met Wild Duncan, a very canny Scot!\"<br />SUMMARY: Intro Duncan of Stoneykirk ([[Hugh McDermott (actor)|Hugh McDermott]]). Duncan, a Highlander, arrives in Sherwood Forest to visit Robin Hood, and hangs around Robin's gang, irritating Robin by flirting with Lady Marian, but what are his real plans?\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=14\n|EpisodeNumber2=14\n|Title=The Wager \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|1|1|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Warren Howard]]\n|DirectedBy=[[Bernard Knowles]]\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"When Robin makes a bet be sure, Normans are the losers; he proves to Friar Tuck that sometimes, beggars can be choosers!\"<br />SUMMARY: When Robin bets Friar Tuck that he can obtain more money by begging than the Friar can by other means, he encounters the unsavoury members of the Beggars guild. Features [[Geoffrey Keen]] as the \"Blind\" Beggar. \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=15\n|EpisodeNumber2=15\n|Title=The Betrothal \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|1|8|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Paul Symonds\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"In Sport it's the professionals, that always win the glory; but Robin is the amateur, and that's a different story!\"<br />SUMMARY: Sir Richard of the Lea, in seeking approval to get his son ([[William Lucas (actor)|William Lucas]]) married off to the lovely Lady Gladys ([[Jennifer Jayne]]), enlists Robins help to persuade her father ([[Charles Lloyd-Pack]]) that his son is suitable.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=16\n|EpisodeNumber2=16\n|Title=The Alchemist\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|1|15|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"The Sheriff thought to set a trap, with witchcraft and an aged hag; but in two ways good Robin, lets the cat out of the bag!\"<br />SUMMARY: A village woman, whose son is an outlaw, is accused of witchcraft for smelting gold coins from stolen plates. Robin must rescue her before she is burned at the stake for consorting with the Devil. Features [[Anthony Sharp]] as The Earl and [[Joyce Blair]] as his wife Millicent.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=17\n|EpisodeNumber2=17\n|Title=A Husband for Marian \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|1|22|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=John Dyson\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Sir Hubert wooed for Marian, he thought his suit was very good; but met a German rival, that was Herr Robin Hood!\"<br />SUMMARY: Marian's father, away at the Crusades, arranges her marriage to Sir Hubert ([[Brian Worth (actor)|Brian Worth]]), a Knight who saved his life. Robin saves Marian from marrying gold digging Sir Hubert by posing as a German Knight who had also been promised Marian's hand in marriage years before, but never turned up to claim it. \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=18\n|EpisodeNumber2=18\n|Title=The Jongleur \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|1|29|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=John Dyson\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"To be a skilful juggler is, a tricky job for any man; especially when Robin juggles with the Sheriff's plans!\"<br />SUMMARY: A Jongleur, Bartholomew ([[Peter Hammond (actor)|Peter Hammond]]), upsets The Sheriff of Nottingham and ends up as Robin's guest for dinner. He is soon recruited to help Robin and Little John in a plan to relieve the Sheriff of the unfair tax money. \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=19\n|EpisodeNumber2=19\n|Title=The Brothers \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|2|5|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"The Sheriff tried to capture Guy, and very hard he pressed the search; so here's how Robin Hood became a patron of the church!\"<br />SUMMARY: Robin & Friar Tuck help a poor serf to enter the Monastery at Whitby. However the young man is forced to flee when the Sheriff has his twin brother thrown into prison on trumped up charges. Robin & Tuck devise a plan to free the man's twin and reunite the two siblings.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=20\n|EpisodeNumber2=20\n|Title=The Intruders \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|2|5|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Paul Symonds\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"In sport it's the professionals, that always win the glory; but Robin is the amateur, and that's a different story!\"<br />SUMMARY: When Robin discovers that two students have been committing robberies and claiming to be his men, Robin and Marian teach them a lesson they'll not forget.<br />NOTE: Minstrel lyrics the same as 'The Betrothal'.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=21\n|EpisodeNumber2=21\n|Title=Errand of Mercy \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|2|6|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=John Dyson\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Robin Hood has many guises, but the strangest on the list; was when he aided Anselm, as a pharmacist!\"<br />SUMMARY: Saint Anthony's Fire is running rampant throughout Nottingham, and it's up to Little John and Robin to deliver much needed supplies to the city, in order to help the poor. However they are discovered and Robin is wounded in battle. It's up to Little John to save the day.<br />NOTE: St Anthony's fire, caused by [[Ergotism]], was caught and spread by eating bread made from [[rye]] contaminated with the fungus ergot. Reported symptoms of the period include convulsions, vomiting, hallucinations and limbs turning black, as if burned by fire, and falling off before death. First reported in France in 994. \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=22\n|EpisodeNumber2=22\n|Title=The Sheriff's Boots \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|2|19|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=James Aldridge <br />& Ralph Smart\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"When the Sheriff wanted boots, his underlings began the war; when Robin finished with the louts, their feet indeed were sore!\"<br />SUMMARY: Having tried all the boots in Nottingham, the Sheriff finds wonderful boots in the village of [[Retford]]. However he soon learns who makes them, and is easily persuaded to let the merchants of Nottingham have their way with the village. [[Joan Sims]] appears as Nell.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=23\n|EpisodeNumber2=23\n|Title=Will Scarlet\n|OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|1956|3}}\n|WrittenBy=[[John Dyson (screenwriter)|John Dyson]]\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Scarlet is a colour that, the Lincoln green does not well suit; but Scarlet in a dandy's hat, becomes a new recruit!\"<br />SUMMARY: At the Blue Boar Inn Robin & Little John walk in on the garishly dressed William of Winchester. Little John insults Will, sword play ensues attracting the Sheriff's men. Robin, John and Will fight them off together. The creation of Will Scarlet begins. Features [[Jennifer Jayne]] as Olivia.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=24\n|EpisodeNumber2=24\n|Title=Ladies of Sherwood\n|OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|1956|3}}\n|WrittenBy=Ralph Smart\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"The Merry Maids of Nottingham, were buxom beauteous and good; but none of them was ever quite, like Mistress Robin Hood!\"<br />SUMMARY: When the town gates are closed to all men until after a hanging, Robin Hood attempts entry disguised as a woman only to be discovered and imprisoned.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=25\n|EpisodeNumber2=25\n|Title= The Deserted Castle\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|3|23|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Eric Heath (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Today we act like diplomats, to his Merry Men bold Robin says; we clear yon castle both of mice and the alliance francais!\"<br />SUMMARY: Marian takes Robin to an ancient and deserted castle, where he is shocked to see the Queen Mother waiting for him. She has a mission for him that will be of tremendous service to England in general and King Richard in particular in denying an alliance between Prince John and King Phillip of France. Final appearance of Jill Esmond as Queen Eleanor.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=26\n|EpisodeNumber2=26\n|Title= The Miser\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|4|8|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Ralph Smart\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"When taxes come a magic spell, turns silver into useless piles; the people understand it well, and all are wreathed in smiles!\"<br />SUMMARY: Sir William ([[Laurence Naismith]]) raises the taxes on his tenant farmers, then threatens to throw them off their land if they don't come up with the money. Robin comes up with a plan to get the villagers their money back, but it involves Friar Tuck keeping them in church while he does so, so Tuck prepares to deliver the longest sermon of his career.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=27\n|EpisodeNumber2=27\n|Title= Trial by Battle\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|4|15|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Arthur Behr]] (pseudonym of [[Waldo Salt]])\n|DirectedBy=[[Terence Fisher]]\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Maid Marian is doomed to hang, brave knights it seems are all too few; of course it's Robin Hood at last, who proves her champion true!\"<br />SUMMARY: Maid Marian is accused of the murder of King's commissioner. Trial by battle is the only hope to stay her execution, but the men of Sherwood feel that Robin is too ill to be her champion. Features [[Nicholas Parsons]] as Sir Walter.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=28\n|EpisodeNumber2=28\n|Title=The May Queen \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|4|22|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Ralph Smart\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Robin Hood and Little John, contrive by means of charade; to save a young man's honour, and unite him with his maid!\" <br />SUMMARY: When Sir Walter ([[Ian Bannen]]) of Donington's father is killed at the [[Third Crusade]], the father of his betrothed, Genevieve Blackstock ([[Gillian Sterrett]]), intendeds to swindle him out of his estate, with help from Count de Clifford who claims he was owed a debt by Lord Donington, Walter counters the claims and is forced to settle the matter in armed combat at the May Fayre, Robin steps in to see fair play. \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=29\n|EpisodeNumber2=29\n|Title=Children of the Greenwood \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|4|29|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=John Cousins\n|DirectedBy=Ralph Smart\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"From out the mouths of babes come pearls of wisdom, at least so they say; to demonstrate dear boys and girls, we bid thee watch our play!\"<br />SUMMARY: When Arthur A'Bland (Arthur Skinner), a serf to Count FitzUrse, is framed for murder on his land, he flees to safety in Sherwood Forest, his children Alice ([[Jane Asher]]) and Oswald ([[Peter Asher]]) are taken in by the Lord FitzUrse (John Longden). Robin sets out to reunite Arthur and his offspring.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=30\n|EpisodeNumber2=30\n|Title=The Vandals \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|5|1|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=C.D. Phipps\n|DirectedBy=Arthur Crabtree\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"When there's a minstrel near, good music can be counted on; unless his name perchance, is Robin Hood or Little John!\".<br />SUMMARY: Masked raiders have slain Ralph Redman and burnt his home, leaving an arrow that points to Robin as the culprit, Robin seeks out the truth at Wells Castle and its new owner Baron Hubert (John Dearth), has his desire to possess his own hunting grounds led him to murder those in his way?\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=31\n|EpisodeNumber2=31\n|Title= The Byzantine Treasure\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|5|6|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Paul Symonds]]\n|DirectedBy=Terence Fisher\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Sir Richard is a doughty knight, who needs no urging to create; impressions of great wealth and might, with borrowed silver plate!\"<br />SUMMARY: Robin unknowingly steals Queen Eleanor's silver Byzantine plates, being transported undercover by a monk through Sherwood. Marian involves their friend Sir Richard of the Lea (Ian Hunter), but Sir Richard, as ever, has many debts to pay off and uses the plates to show how wealthy he is. Soon the Sheriff's lieutenant ([[William Squire]]) takes an interest \u2013 can Robin hold him off until the Archbishop arrives to take the plates to their rightful owner? \n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=32\n|EpisodeNumber2=32\n|Title=The Wanderer \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|5|13|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Albert G. Ruben\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Joseph helps an outlaw's son, and is the Sheriff's enemy; but Robin's duel is swiftly won, and both escape Scot free!\"<br />SUMMARY: Intro Joseph of Cordoba (Karl Stepanek). Robin meets travelling physician Joseph of Cordoba, who is reported to the Sheriff when he upsets the local \"doctors\" by curing the ailing Sir Walter de Lys, when they couldn't. When Derwent's ([[Victor Woolf]]) son is injured Robin seeks Joseph's help, but the Sheriff is waiting to trap Derwent, and Robin must save the day. <br />NOTE: Victor Woolf and Paula Byrne are incorrectly billed as Edward and Edward's Wife on the end titles. Woolf, in fact, plays his usual recurring outlaw character Derwent, identified in dialogue as 'Derwent the Joiner', with Byrne as his wife. Paula Byrne also appears as Derwent's wife, named Ethel, in the episode 'Errand of Mercy'.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=33\n|EpisodeNumber2=33\n|Title=The Youngest Outlaw \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|5|18|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=John Dyson\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Once a boy to Sherwood came, to live beneath the greenwood tree; hoping he could hide his fame, as Duke of Brittany!\"<br />SUMMARY: The future King of England, prince Arthur (Peter Asher) is lost in the greenwood. Robin finds him and works to return him to his mother [[Constance, Duchess of Brittany]] ([[Dorothy Alison]]), while Little John teaches the boy outlaw ways. Robin is tricked and hands the boy over to those who wish him harm. Features Bruce Seton as Lord Torrence.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=34\n|EpisodeNumber2=34\n|Title=The Traitor \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|