h nothing huge he's not too small; to show six knights to their mischance, he's not so gentle at all!\"<br />SUMMARY: The mysterious pilgrim Peregrinus ([[Patrick Barr]]) arrives in Nottingham and is not all he seems.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=38\n|EpisodeNumber2=38\n|Title=Richard the Lion-Heart \n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|6|17|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Paul Symonds\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Peregrinus is in fact, King Richard of the Lion-Heart; with Robin Hood to guard the realm, the King can then depart!\"<br />SUMMARY: Having obtained the list of traitors conspiring to put Prince John on the throne, King Richard/Peregrinus plans to capture the rebel lords' leader, Count de Belvoir, the Earl of Huntingdon.\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=39\n|EpisodeNumber2=39\n|Title= The Scientist\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|6|23|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Neil R. Collins\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Tyrant old and tyrant new, turn science to their evil ends; Albertus keeps his secret, until all men are friends!\"<br />SUMMARY:  The Abbot ([[Charles Lloyd-Pack]]) entrusts the safety of Albertus of Oxford ([[Miles Malleson]]), a master of science who is wanted by Prince John to construct a device to destroy ships at sea, to Friar Tuck. Can Robin get the monk to safety or will the Sheriff claim the prize?\n|LineColor=BFF0FF\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series 2 (1956\u201357)===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"\n!style=\"background:#F3CE4E; width:20px\"|N\u00ba\n!style=\"background:#F3CE4E; width:20px\"|Ep\n!style=\"background:#F3CE4E\"|Title\n!style=\"background:#F3CE4E\"|Director\n!style=\"background:#F3CE4E\"|Screenplay\n!style=\"background:#F3CE4E; width:135px\"|Original air date\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=1\n|EpisodeNumber=40\n|Title= The Prisoner\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|8|10|df=y}} \n|WrittenBy=Anne Rodney (pseudonym of [[Howard E. Koch|Howard Koch]] and Anne Koch)\n|DirectedBy=[[Bernard Knowles]]\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"A song has come to Robin's ears, from deep beneath the palace ground; it tells that Richard is alive, and John shall not be crowned!\"<br />SUMMARY: Prince John ([[Donald Pleasence]]) has issued a decree that King Richard is dead and that he will be crowned King, Marian and Robin head to London and the Prince's palace to stop the [[Coronation]] taking place by proving Richard still lives, can Robin free the King's messenger from the Holy Land held in John's dungeon in time?<br />NOTE: This episode makes use of the folk song 'All around my Hat', said by Robin to be a favourite of Richard's in the Holy Land, though it would seem it wasn't written until the 19th Century.\n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=2\n|EpisodeNumber=41\n|Title=Blackmail\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|9|30|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Neil R. Collins\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"To foil a blackmail scheme and save, Sir Richard from a vicious jest; Robin names the Sheriff and, the Sheriff does the rest!\"<br />SUMMARY: Prince John is to visit Nottingham, Lucas ([[Anthony Dawson]]) a wine merchant falls asleep in the back of his wagon, which is stolen by Robin's gang, he overhears Robin talking with Lady Marian, for the visit she has to have 3 unwelcome guests, and Sir Richard of the Lea ([[Ian Hunter (actor)|Ian Hunter]]) has to have 40, so Robin takes the wine cart to his castle, Lucas overhears Robins conversation with Sir Richard and sees the potential for blackmail.\n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=3\n|EpisodeNumber=42\n|Title=A Year and A Day\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|10|14|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Neil R. Collins]]\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"In public view the whole day through, remains the serf who's run away; the Sheriff sounds the 'cry and hue', but freedom wins the day!\"<br />SUMMARY: Under Medieval English law, a peasant who escapes serfdom and lives in a city for \"a year and a day\" is a free man, given the man lives openly, not in hiding. Surgeon Calend (Shaun O'Riordan) has nearly completed that duration, and only has to remain 'at large' until sunset that day and he will be free, the Sheriff closes in on him whilst he is treating Little John. When Robin hears Calend's story he agrees to help, the Sheriff invokes the law of \"hue and cry\", explaining that any man within hearing must drop his chores and help apprehend the felon. \n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=4\n|EpisodeNumber=43\n|Title=Ransom\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|10|28|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[John Dyson (screenwriter)|John Dyson]]\n|DirectedBy=[[Terence Fisher]]\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"The price of honour is too high, when villagers must be oppressed; but Joan the barmaid snares Sir Guy, and Robin does the rest!\"<br />SUMMARY: When the Count de Severne decrees the heavily taxed villagers must also raise the 500 crown ransom for his son, they turn to Robin for help. Guy Quentin ([[Paul Daneman]]) reveals the reason for the ransom and Robin turns the tables with Joan's help.\n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=5\n|EpisodeNumber=44\n|Title=The Goldmaker\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|10|29|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Paul Symonds\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"From rags to riches he will go, Sir Richard is told; alas he is not the first to find, that glitter is not gold!\"<br />SUMMARY: intro for Lepidus, ([[Alfie Bass]]) the Alchemist. Hearing he is deep in debt, Robin & Marian call on Sir Richard of the Lea, and find he has fallen under the influence of Lepidus the Alchemist, who has promised to turn his pewter plates to gold, having proved his alchemy 'works'. The Sheriff wants to arrest Lepidus for treason but Robin, after proving Lepidus 'powers' to him, parleys a deal with the greedy Sheriff to give over the alchemist in exchange for Will (Shaun O'Riordan), an outlaw that is to be hanged.\n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}} \n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=6\n|EpisodeNumber=45\n|Title=The Haunted Mill\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|11|4|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Paul Symonds\n|DirectedBy=[[Lindsay Anderson]]\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"A plague of mice, a stream run dry, has filled the miller with alarm; to catch the villain, Little John must lend his strong right arm!\"<br />SUMMARY: intro Tom the Miller ([[James Hayter (actor)|James Hayter]]). When Sir William (Laurence Hardy) tries to acquire Tom the Miller's flour mill by underhand means, Robin is soon called in to save the day.\n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=7\n|EpisodeNumber=46\n|Title=The Imposters\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|11|5|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Norman Best]]\n|DirectedBy=Lindsay Anderson\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"It's very strange the husbands three, she seems to have that lady proud; then maids and blades make Robin see, the truth that three's a crowd!\"<br />SUMMARY: Lady Pomfret's ([[Brenda De Banzie]]) husband hasn't returned from the Crusades for seven years, and under the law he is deemed to be dead, her cousin LeBlonde ([[Edward Mulhare]]) has arrived to take possession of her estate, will an imposter, or two, help the situation?. \n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=8\n|EpisodeNumber=47\n|Title=The Hero\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|11|11|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=John Dyson\n|DirectedBy=Terence Fisher\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Mistakes made in history, about who's hero and who's not; but Robin solves the mystery, and thus unfolds our plot!\"<br />SUMMARY: The unpopular tax collector Sir Montichet ([[Ralph Michael]]) is killed, Mark ([[Bill Owen (actor)|Bill Owen]]) an opportunist thief sees the murder, and is blamed for it, the villagers let him escape reasoning it was self-defence, Mark takes with him the name of the real killer written in blood on a parchment by the victim. Robin welcomes him into his band, but the victim was The Sheriff's brother and he plans to hang eight villagers unless Mark gives himself up.\n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=9\n|EpisodeNumber=48\n|Title=Isabella\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|11|19|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Neil R. Collins\n|DirectedBy=Lindsay Anderson\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"The Lady Isabella is as sweet it seems that she can be; she smiles she sighs she cries, but don't believe all that you see!\"<br />SUMMARY: [[Isabel, Countess of Gloucester|Princess Avice of Gloucester]] ([[Helen Cherry]]), Prince John's wife, secretly summons Robin to the [[Tower of London]], Prince John ([[Donald Pleasence]]) is planning to marry a French Princess, and so she sends Robin to Dover to intercept Lady [[Isabella of Angouleme]] ([[Zena Walker]]) and make her see the error of her ways.<br />NOTE: in this episode, at the Blue Boar Inn, a minstrel sings \"The Ballad of Barbara Alan\", however the earliest known version of this song is from the 15th century. \n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}} \n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=10\n|EpisodeNumber=49\n|Title=The Black Patch\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|11|25|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[John Dyson (screenwriter)|John Dyson]]\n|DirectedBy=[[Terry Bishop]]\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Sir Dunston comes to Nottingham, it\u2019s clear he\u2019s up to nothing good; he captivates Maid Marian, and captures Robin Hood!\"<br />SUMMARY: Sir Dunston of the Black Patch ([[Duncan Lamont]]) arrives at Fitzwilliam Hall, he tells Marian that he has sworn to wear the patch over his left eye until he has captured Robin Hood and seen him swing from the gallows in London, having laid a false rumour that he is carrying gold to Scotland, which Marian has passed on to the outlaws, he sets off through Sherwood to capture Robin when he tries to steal it, can Marian warn Robin off in time? \n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=11\n|EpisodeNumber=50\n|Title=Outlaw Money\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|12|2|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[John Dyson (screenwriter)|John Dyson]]\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Villagers are being starved, the outlaws quickly take the hint; and making money\u2019s not so hard, when Robin has the mint!\"<br />SUMMARY: Henry ([[Sid James]]), Master of the Nottingham Mint, falls foul of the Sheriff's men when they catch him with Robin, The Sheriff takes this opportunity to bring in his own Minter ([[Leonard Sachs]]), Henry mints pure silver dinars for the starving villagers of Lottham at Robin's camp, when they try to spend them at the market, they are denounced as counterfeit and Friar Tuck is arrested and put on trial for forgery, Henry must prove that the Sheriff's coinage is impure, silver mixed with base metal and illegal under the law.\n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=12\n|EpisodeNumber=51\n|Title=Hubert\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|12|9|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Ralph Smart <br />& Ann Rodney\n|DirectedBy=Terence Fisher\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Sir Hubert is the kind of Knight, who cannot fence and cannot fight; he doesn't know a lance by sight, nor left hand from the right!\"<br />SUMMARY: Sir Hubert ([[William Greene (actor)|William Greene]]) seeks Robin's help to reunite him with his true love Rowena ([[Dorothy Bromiley]]) whose father, Sir Thomas ([[William Mervyn]]) is marrying her off to a local lord ([[Richard Pascoe]]), Robin is soon at work on his behalf.\n|LineColor=F3CE4E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=13\n|EpisodeNumber=52\n|Title=The Trap\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1956|12|16|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Charles Early]]\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"The Sheriff 