othy Cox ([[Kenneth Cope]]) must win the hand of Mary Quatermaine ([[Ann Firbank]]), against her Uncle's wishes, by beating Pierre of Bordeaux (Paul Eddington) in an archery contest. Hopeless with the longbow, Robin lends a hand by taking Timothy to a [[Bowyer]] to learn the art of bow making. The final round of the contest is shooting an apple in the air.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=10\n|EpisodeNumber=86\n|Title=The Angry Village\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|11|10|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Shirl Hendryx\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: During a drought, a group of villagers led by Jason ([[Harry H. Corbett]]) are hiding grain in a cave; despite posting a lookout, soldiers from the castle appear without warning and take it. Strangers in the area Robin and Little John are blamed by the villagers and flee. Jason seeks out Robin for help to find out how they were betrayed before another innocent person is blamed by the villagers. Villagers include [[Geoffrey Bayldon]], [[Rowland Bartrop]], [[Leonard Sharp]]\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=11\n|EpisodeNumber=87\n|Title=The Mark\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|11|17|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Robert Newman\n|DirectedBy=Robert Day\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Friar tuck takes Robin, Little John and Derwent to visit Master stone mason Walter ([[Philip Ray]]) with his apprentice Diccon ([[Kenneth Cope]]), who are at work rebuilding a ruined church for Sir Blaise De Roche ([[Charles Gray (actor)|Charles Gray]]), but the lord has plans to fortify the building and holds Walter prisoner until he agrees to the modifications. The outlaws rescue the mason to ensure the structure stays a holy one.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=12\n|EpisodeNumber=88\n|Title=The Bride of Robin Hood\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|11|24|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Oliver Skene (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=[[Anthony Squire]]\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Brenda ([[Billie Whitelaw]]), after saving Robin from the Sheriff's men, is voted a member of Robin's band. Brenda believes it her destiny to marry a hero and she becomes a distraction to Robin's men and he is railroaded into agreeing to marry her. Maid Marian is not amused especially after being robbed by Brenda and decides she and Robin must reunite her with Walter Neville ([[Ronald Allen]]), her betrothed.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=13\n|EpisodeNumber=89\n|Title=To Be A Student\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|12|1|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Sidney B. Wells\n|DirectedBy=Robert Day\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Rolfe (Paul Eddington) to avoid his son Jack ([[Roger Bizley]]) from having to join Prince John's army, bribes Master Bement ([[Hugh Moxey]]) to make sure the scholarly Peter Larkin ([[Derek Waring]]) is taken instead. Robin ensures fair play.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=14\n|EpisodeNumber=90\n|Title=The Challenge of the Black Knight\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|12|8|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Leon Griffiths\n|DirectedBy=Anthony Squire\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: On his 14th birthday, Will Dale ([[Richard O'Sullivan]]), the son of Ned a member of Robin's gang, meets Robin and goes hunting with Little John; a confrontation with the Black Knight, Sir Roger Fitzwilliam ([[John Arnatt]]), leads to Robin being challenged to a duel with the Knight.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=15\n|EpisodeNumber=91\n|Title=The Rivals\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|12|15|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Leslie Poynton\n|DirectedBy=Robert Day\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: The Sheriff wants to charge a protection tax from travellers through Sherwood forest; knowing this will be unpopular, he comes up with a rival gang, to rob and attack travellers, made up of prisoners. His [[Seneschal]] (Paul Eddington) suggests the prisoners are led by Dick Banks (Carl Bernard). When Friar Tuck is robbed by a prisoner he knows, Robin has Tuck join the Nottingham Traders guild to discover the sheriff's plans that include betraying the robbers. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=16\n|EpisodeNumber=92\n|Title=The Christmas Goose\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|12|22|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Oliver Skene (pseudonym of [[Ring Lardner, Jr.]])\n|DirectedBy=Don Chaffey\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Davey's ([[Jon Whiteley]]) goose, Matilda, nips a Lord's horse causing him to be thrown. The Lord, Sir Leon ([[Jack Watling]]), puts the animal on trial, as he hopes to condemn the goose to death \u2013 for his Christmas dinner. Friar Tuck is called on by Davey and unsuccessfully defends the goose and soon Robin puts his mind to the problem by making the Lord's young daughter Susan's ([[Jane Asher]]), who he dotes on, Christmas day miserable. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=17\n|EpisodeNumber=93\n|Title=A Village Wooing\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|12|27|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Neil R. Collins\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=INTRODUCTORY MINSTREL SONG: \"Many reasons have been claimed, for joining Robin's merry band; the stranger was a lad who aimed to win his true love's hand!\"<br />SUMMARY: Robin tries to help Wat Longfellow ([[Leslie Phillips]]), who became an outlaw to escape a life of indentured servitude, win the hand of the independent Widow Winifred ([[Betty Impey]]), but the wily Bailiff Baldwin ([[Donald Pleasence]]) also desires her.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=18\n|EpisodeNumber=94\n|Title=The Profiteer\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|12|29|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Samuel B. West\n|DirectedBy=Terry Bishop\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: When Andrew ([[Gordon Jackson (actor)|Gordon Jackson]]) a serf, arrives in Nottingham to obtain grain to feed the villagers of Lothan, as their crops have failed. Robin gives him the money to buy the grain and he impresses grain farmer, Hodges ([[John Longden]]), who is looking for a good man to marry his daughter, Margaret ([[Barbara Archer]]), thinking Andrew a 'freeman'. To buy his freedom he is tempted to sell the grain at a vast profit until Robin helps put things on the right path.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=19\n|EpisodeNumber=95\n|Title=Knight Errant\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|1|5|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Michael Connor (screenwriter)|Michael Connor]]\n|DirectedBy=[[Anthony Squire]]\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Marian's father has rewarded a knight for saving his life with her hand in marriage. A jealous Robin has to see off the roguish gold digger Sir Jack of Southwark ([[William Lucas (actor)|William Lucas]]) who makes an impression on Marian and the Sheriff does not want Sir Jack marrying Marian and accuses him of murder. \n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=20\n|EpisodeNumber=96\n|Title=The Healing Hand\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|1|12|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=Leon Griffiths\n|DirectedBy=Bernard Knowles\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Oswald ([[Michael Ripper]]) a 'quack' [[peddler|pedlar]] of phoney medicine befriends Little John, but the outlaw comes to grief when he defends the 'quack' against Baron Barclay's (Bryan Coleman) tax collectors at Bingham fayre and is imprisoned. Oswald goes to Robin and they go to Barclay's castle to convince him he is ill and get the key to Little John's cell.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber2=21\n|EpisodeNumber=97\n|Title=One Man's Meat\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1958|1|19|df=y}}\n|WrittenBy=George & Gertrude Fass\n|DirectedBy=Don Chaffey\n|ShortSummary=SUMMARY: Sir Edmund Woodstock ([[Robin Bailey]]) demonstrates his 'Ambrosia Nova' (the Food of the Gods) to Thadeus Goldfinch ([[Kevin Stoney]]), Robin and Friar Tuck. Goldfinch storms out unimpressed with it as human food, and his serfs on the same diet are weakening. Robin and Friar Tuck with the help of a donkey and Goldfinch's pigs find a more receptive audience for the foodstuff.\n|LineColor=195905\n}}